 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Poobah Goladus</span><br>  Posts: 2594<br> <font color=#333333>(1/26/03 1:10:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=375.topic&index=200>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Root for Mages</span><hr size=1> I'm not arguing that we shouldn't get root.  I was more explaining why we don't and pointing out an exaggeration about enchanters.<br>
<br>
I believe are pets are good defense.  Whether you convince me otherwise or not really has little to no bearing on whether or not I think we should have root.  If our ability to summon pets and heal them has no defensive value, then that is what needs to be fixed.  <br>
<br>
I just don't feel that root is in character for mages, either in a roleplaying sense nor in a game balance sense.  And when I say balance I do not mean overpowering, I'm talking about the fact that everquest is about interaction with other classes.<br>
<br>
Each class has strengths and weaknesses, and preserving them is key to that fundamental game concept of class interaction.  The idea is to group with other classes whose strengths will make up for your weaknesses.  The primary weakness of magicians is that they have no ability to control a fight.  Once you are grouped with a class that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>can</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> control a fight, that weakness is mostly gone.<br>
<br>
Our defensive ability is considerable, in my opinion.. but I believe a large part of it is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>potential</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, not raw.  Magicians get defensive <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>potential</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which can be realized by grouping with classes that can buff and heal your pet.  This potential can also be realized in a more personal way by pet-healing or chain casting pets.<br>
<br>
Our offensive ability is considerable and does not rely on an unusually large contribution from any other classes.<br>
<br>
I'm a visual person and here's how I'd imagine things as a mage.  (+ represents actual, o represents potential)<br>
<br>
Offense +++++++ooo (7/10)<br>
Defense +++ooo (3/6)<br>
Control  + (1/1)<br>
Misc Utility ++ooo (2/5)<br>
<br>
<br>
Wizards might be<br>
<br>
Offense +++++ooooo (5/10)<br>
Defense ++ (2/2)<br>
Control*  ++++oo (4/6)<br>
Misc Utility +oo (1/3)<br>
<br>
*I considered Concussion as potential control, best used to keep a mobs attention focused on a tank not you.  While that is a defensively oriented ability, I still considered it directly controlling mobs.<br>
<br>
Warriors might be<br>
<br>
Offense ++++oooo (4/<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
Defense +++++ooooo (5/10)<br>
Control ++ (2/2)<br>
Misc. Utility (0/0)<br>
<br>
<br>
Enchanters<br>
<br>
Offense ++++++o (6/7) (I know, charm-- I don't care)<br>
Defense ++ (2/2)<br>
Control +++++++ooo (7/10)<br>
Misc. Utility +++ooo (3/6) <br>
<br>
<br>
Obviously that's all just raw, random, unscientific thinking and it doesn't include how you actually realize the potential, but even here you can see that these classes complement each other.  The enchanter and wizard have very little defense but between them have a good deal of control.  The wizard and the mage give superior offense to the warrior and enchanter, and the mage and warrior provide the defense.<br>
<br>
Theoretically, this group of four should be able to kill things that are <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">more</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> than 4 times more difficult than something that any one of them could kill on their own.  In practice the only reason this wouldn't be true is there is still a weakness:  No healer.<br>
<br>
This is one reason that the pet aggro rules are STUPID.  They do not promote player interaction.  The pet aggro rules promote the exclusion of melees, which is bad for the game.  I'm sorry but that fix was probably one of the sloppiest hack-job fixes I've ever seen in EQ.  A friend predicted that it would eventually haunt them, and I totally agreed with him, and finally in PoP it's coming true.  All-pet groups exclude melees, as do groups using charmed pets.  In these situations melees generally cost more than the value they return.<br>
<br>
Ok sorry for the gigantic rambling post.  If you only read the first two paragraphs you prolly didn't miss anything interesting <p><center><br>
